"Near the Ceraunian rocks our course we bore— The shortest passage to the’ Italian shore. Now had the sun withdrawn his radiant light, And hills were hid in dosky shades of night: ‘We land, and, on the bosom of the ground, A safe retreat and a bare lodging found. Close by the shore we lay ; the sailors keep Their watches, and the rest securely sleep. The night, proceeding on with silent pace, Stood in her neon, and view'd with equal face % Her steepy rise, and her declining race. Then wakeful Palinurus rose, to spy The face of heaven, and the nocturnal sky ; And listen’d every breath of air to try;"